Fig. 6

a showed the fluorescence intensity changes of sensor BA-N-CDs with addition of increasing concentrations of Fe3+solution. The fluorescence quenching process of sensor BA-N-CDs occurred with a redshift (> 30 nm) in emissive wavelength. Compared with many reported Fe3+ probes, the fluorescence titration performance of sensor BA-N-CDs with Fe3+ exhibited obvious difference. As listed in some literatures (listed in Table 1
), Fe3+ could quench the fluorescence of sensor effectively, but no additional fluorescence emission is produced. Herein, at the same time that the yellow fluorescence was quenched, the bright red fluorescence appeared. The fluorescence changes from yellow to red provided us with important enlightenment for constructing highly selective fluorescence sensor of Fe3+ based on CDs. Further, by fluorescence titration spectrum linear fitting (Figure S5), the detection limit was confirmed and achieved 2.45 nM level, which exhibited high sensitivity compared with reported Fe3+ fluorescence sensors [42–56] and also indicated that the sensor BA-N-CDs could track trace Fe3+ in water environment (Table 1).

In addition, in plant physiological systems, iron disorder will affect the photosynthetic efficiency of plants, thus resulting in a decrease in yield. Furthermore, iron disorder also affects plant root development, energy metabolism and azotification, resulting in a decreased ability to absorb water and nutrients. So it is of great significance to detect iron ions in plants in real time. As an effective fluorescence sensor for Fe3+, the Fe3+ sensing property in plant system need be studied to expand the application of BA-N-CDs probe. Herein, we choose tomato leaf as experimental specimen (Part S2 and 
                        Fig. 9
                        ). 100 uL BA-N-CDs water solution was injected into leaf and maintained for 5 min, the fluorescence signals were recorded. Then 100 uL Fe3+ water solution was added to above leaf and observed the fluorescence signal constantly. From the Fig. 9. the chloroplastid subcellular structure in tomato leaf was lighted by sensor BA-N-CDs, which showed specific yellow emission and also proved the high permeability in chloroplastid. After treatment with Fe3+ water solution, the fluorescence emission produced a noticeable change from yellow to red. Based on the changes of fluorescence emission, the fluorescence sensor could be utilized as a highly selective and sensitive fluorescence sensor for Fe3+ in plant, especially chloroplasts, which provided us an import analytical tool for changes of iron ions in chloroplasts.
